title: For Sale/Trade:  !!Colt OP !!NICE!!
postcontent:
Colt means QUALITY.  Period.  I have a early Colt Official Police .38 SPCL. Caliber revolver.  These are the ancestor to the Python.  They definitely have the "Snake Gun," look as they both share the same frame.  The pre-war models have the rounded "half moon" front sight, checkered trigger, hammer, and cylinder release, and the old style cylinder retention system.   It has a  4” barrel.  Very unique number and uber rare "1" shield number stamped on the butt end.  It was manufactured during WW2(1944) making it very desirable in collectors value.  It has the original Walnut grips embossed with bright Colt medallions.  The checkering is still sharp and defined.  The Post WW2 (1947-54)guns were fitted with plastic grips and are therefore  less sought after.  The bluing is all original and in excellent condition, with only minor localized cosmetic fading towards the barrels end.  Internal barrel and bore are bright, rifling is sharp without any visual deterioration or flaws.  Cylinder timing is perfect with zero play in cylinder lock up.  As well as the cylinder rotates smooth as the day it was manufactured.  As with most early Colts the metal to wood fit is exceptional, as well as the metal to metal machining tolerances. Impeccable quality and functionality.  Current market value on the Guns International site range from $600- $1500+ for this gun model.  I would respectively place the value of this revolver somewhere definitely on the high side of that price spectrum.  As close to "minty," for a 71 year old vintage.  Again this is an all original  war era Colt. A time capsule of American history.  This is a jewel in the current  era of "throw away, disposable," guns.   NO SHIPPING, FACE TO FACE with Florida ID. Serious Inquiries only.  Responses without phone numbers will be ignored. 
I REPEAT, IF YOU ARE NOT A FLORIDA RESIDENT WITH ID,OR IF YOU HAVE AN OUT OF STATE AREA CODE,  DO NOT CONTACT ME!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Heckler & Koch p30L
postcontent:
Introduced in 2008, the P30L (for Long), has a slide and barrel that measure approximately a half-inch longer in length. Otherwise the P30L is essentially identical to the P30.

Like the P30, the P30L was designed as a modern police and security pistol and combines optimal function and safety. Ergonomic features include a special grip frame with interchangeable backstraps inserts and lateral plates, allowing the pistol to be individually adapted to any user.

Ambidextrous controls include dual slide releases, magazine release levers, and a serrated decocking button located on the rear of the frame (for applicable variants). A Picatinny rail molded into the front of the frame makes mounting lights, laser aimers, or other accessories easy and convenient. The extractor serves as a loaded chamber indicator providing a reminder of a loaded chamber that can be subtly seen and felt. The standard P30L is a 9 mm “Variant 3 (V3)” with a conventional double-action/single action trigger mode with a serrated decocking button on the rear of the slide.

P30LS models have the features of the “L” model with the addition of an ambidextrous safety lever mounted on both sides of the frame. LS models are available in conventional double-action/single action trigger mode with decocking button (“V3S” 9 mm and .40 S&W) and with HK’s enhanced double action only “V2” Law Enforcement Modification trigger. A special “V1” lightweight trigger pull model of the Law Enforcement Modification is also available.

Extensively tested, P30L and P30LS models have been adopted by several international police and security agencies. Excellent weight and balance make the P30L naturally pointable, easy to control, and accurate to shoot. An open notch rear sight with luminous (non-radioactive) contrast points allows for fast and accurate target acquisition, even under poor lighting conditions

title: For Sale:  Fujinon 16x70 FMT-SX Polaris Binoculars w/ Lifetime Warranty
postcontent:
Unfortunately it has come for me to sell the best pair of binoculars I have ever owned or looked through. The only reason I'm selling these is because I need to consolidate and am thus buying binoculars with rangefinding capabilities. The binoculars come with everything I received when they were ordered last March: box, carrying case, neck strap, manual, warranty card, receipt, etc. I'll even throw in my Leopold Bino Tripod adapter which I bought for around $25.

Before buying these binoculars, I spent weeks doing research. I wanted the absolute best binoculars I could get my hands on for my upcoming sheep hunt last fall. Prior to the Fuji's, I was using the Nikon Monarchs, which were decent, and in my opinion, outperformed everything except the top tier's, like Leica, Swarovski, Zeiss, and Vortex Razors (however, I'll concede that I never had the chance to compare them to the german bino's, i.e., Steiner, Minox, or Docter-Nobilem). But the Fuji's topped them all and have been the best optic I have ever used, at least in the category of optical quality. They aren't the lightest, but they're durable, and the color, clarity, and light transmission cannot be beaten, and these qualities are more important to me than weight anyway. They are, of course, waterproof, fogproof, nitrogen filled, etc. Come with a lifetime warranty, see picture.

I honestly cannot say enough good things about this optic. For example, usually, I was always the first one to spot elk, especially in low light conditions, and on one occasion, the elk I was looking at couldn't even be seen with my partner's Swarovski EL 10x50's. He had to borrow my binoculars to see the elk and I couldn't the elk with his. From that day on, if we were together (and if he didn't have to pack them up the mountain) he was always asking to spot with my Fuji's. On my aforementioned sheep hunt, I was able to spot Mountain Goats at least three miles away AT MIDNIGHT. Also, I am able to see craters and spots on the moon I have never seen before. And, one reviewer on binoculars.com talks about how he was glassing Jupitor's Moons with these binoculars.

I have taken immaculate care of these binoculars, as I do with all my hunting equipment I'm a fanatic about keeping lens covers on my optics, so you can be assured that lenses are in great shape. You can see my seller feedback if you search for these binoculars on ebay.

What turned me onto Fuji optics was their outstanding reviews on allbinos.com. I relied on this site to buy my Nikon's and I was really happy with them. I was even happier with my Fuji's. If you take nothing else away from this ad, trust and use allbinos.com.

Here are the allbino rankings for the 10x50 category, you'll notice what ranks second, by a very narrow margin: http://www.allbinos.com/allbinos_ranking-binoculars_ranking-10x50.html The only difference from the model they used in their rankings and the model I'm selling, besides the difference in the size of the lenses, is that they used a model that had a rubber armored coating, which is what the R stands for in FMTR-SX. But Fuji doesn't make the fully rubberized version for the 16x70's, so the model there is FMT-SX. They do still have some rubber, but it must not be as thick or something.

The binoculars were made in Japan, which has a reputation for making great glass (all of the Vortex Razor stuff comes from there), and they boast a 95% light transmission rating which trumps both the top of the line Leica (90.6% -- albino.com) and Swarovski (90%) and matches that of the Zeiss (95%).

I should caution you by stating that these binoculars are big and won't fit into all of the commercial chest harnesses out there.

The pictured features are from Eagle Optics - http://www.eagleoptics.com/binoculars/fujinon/fujinon-polaris-16x70-fmt-sx-binocular

More pictures can be seen here: http://www.ebay.com/itm/REDACTED72?ssPageName=STRK:MESELX:IT&_trksid=p3984.m1555.l2649

Happy Holidays!!

WW 2, SPRINGFIELD ARMORY, M1 GARAND, 30-06 (LETTERKENNY REBUILD 1965)

The title says it all, this M1 is simply beautifu as an investment and as a shooter. It is a higly regarded Letterkenny Army Depot (LEAD) arsenal rebuild. It is the most collectable of all rebuilds with the beautiful “Silver” finish only produced at this depot. Matched with the correct LEAD stock and given a WW2 Serial you have an incredibly collectable and highly valued rifle. However, with this particular firearm it gets better. Let me explain.

We have known production numbers from the Springfield armory for month to month during the war. In September 2013, Ruger began production of the Ruger American in Mayodan NC. The boxes of the first 1,000 rifles were affixed with a special "First Production Run" sticker. title: For Sale/Trade:  Bushmaster about to be sued ?!?!
postcontent:
It appears that the parents of the "Newtown" tragedy (or the lawyers involved, I am sure) have decided that they will sue Bushmaster firearms for manufacturing the gun that was used in the shooting. When will this kind of foolishness stop, if ever? Newtown was a terrible tragedy, period.  But, Bushmaster was not at fault...that is pretty apparent. Guns are legal, safe and have never hurt anyone, on their own...and neither has Bushmaster.
If I go fishing.... and catch a shark and the shark bites my arm off, can I sue Zebco if I was using their fishing rod when I caught my fish. Can I sue Fruit of the Loom if I was wearing their socks when it happened?
It is a chance for someone (zealous lawyers for certain) to make a profit off of this event. There was / is a guilt party here...it is not Bushmaster.
The parents of Newtown have also decided to sue the entire town of Newtown for that one young man's actions. In other words, bankrupt a town/city, because you can. Our legal system is so tilted, some of this will probably actually hold water.
Integrity, honesty, taking responsibility and putting it where it belongs, what are those concepts?

title: For Sale:  BRAND NEW KEL TEC KSG FOR $799
postcontent:
The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNC’s first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1” overall length and an 18.5” cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3” rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward. CONTACT KENNY AT REDACTED FOR MORE INFORMATION!!!!!!!

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1942 trench shotgun with 30" barrel
postcontent: This is a 1942 Winchester model 1897 known as a trench gun. The designer was John Browning. It is 12 gauge with full choke. It is a "slam gun", i.e. hold the trigger down and when you pump it fires repeatedly. The barrel is 30 inches. "The model97 became the most popular shotgun on the American market and established a standard of performance by which other kinds and makes of shotguns were judged, including the most expensive export.". This is a "plain" gun. The furniture has sparatic marks and cuts but not substantial. The finish is worn. This weapon was used and the patina in excellent. I have fired this weapon and it is in perfect firing condition without flaws.

title: For Sale:  MSAR STG 556 OD Bullpup Rifle + Extras
postcontent:
Selling a MSAR STG 556 in excellent condition plus 3 magazines (1x40rd, 1x30rd, 1x20rd) and flip up sights

About MSAR
The STG-556 rifle was developed by US-based company Microtec Small Arms Research, a sister company to famous hi-tech knife-maker Microtec Knives Co. Based on the famous Austrian Steyr AUG assault rifle. Manufacture of this clone became possible because original patents for  SteyrAUG have expired, and the demand for civilian version of this weapon in USA was not covered by import of original Austrian-made rifles. MSAR designers took some time to reverse-engineer the Steyr AUG,and then added several additional features that they feel might appeal to US shooters. Most notable of these new features are bolt stop release button and Ar-15 style bolt -closure forward assist button on the left side of receiver. Otherwise, the STG-556 follows the  Steyr AUG A2 rifle pattern. Microtec MSARSTG-556 rifle is available in different colors and with barrels of various lengths. Optional caliber conversion kit allows to upgrade the rifle from 5.56mm / .223 to more potent 6.8mm Rem SPC caliber. SAR also offers STG-556 in either semi-automatic only (civilian / police) or selective-fire (military) versions.

Microtec MSARSTG-556 rifle is gas-operated semi-automatic or selective-fired weapon of bullpup configuration. The receiver is made from aluminum alloy, the stock / housing is made from impact-resistant polymer. Barrels are quick-detachable, with barrel lock incorporated into the gas block /forward grip base. Gas system features short-stroke gas piston, located to the right of the barrel. Bolt group rides on dual guide rods, and different user-replaceable multi-lug rotary bolts are available for right- or left-hand ejection. STG-556 is equipped with bolt hold-open device; bolt catch release button is located on the left side of the gun, behind the magazine housing. The M16 / Ar-15 type bolt closure assist button is located on the left side of the gun, in front of the magazine. Non-reciprocating charging handle is located also on the leftside, in front of the receiver. STG-556 accepts proprietary Steyr AUG-type magazines, made of plastic; magazine release button is located below the stock, behind the magazine housing. Manual safety is of cross-bolt button style, located above the pistol grip. In military select-fire version, mode of fire is controlled by the pull of the trigger - short pull results in single shots, long pull produces full automatic fire.STG-556 is offered either with Steyr AUG-type1.5X magnification telescope sight on special detachable mount, or with Picatinny rail (also on detachable base).

Aimpoint CompM4 sights are the finest sights that Aimpoint has ever produced. The improved energy efficiency provides up to 8 years of continuous use from a single AA battery! Aimpoint CompM4 sights incorporate an integral mount that eliminates the need for a separate ring and can be customized with vertical and forward spacers to fit a variety of firearms. They can also be used by hunters and sport shooters that need night vision compatibility. CompM4 sights are available in two versions. The Aimpoint CompM4 is now the latest version of the US Army's M68 CCO (Close-Combat Optic), continuing a legacy that Aimpoint has maintained since 1997. The performance of the CompM4 sights is optimized for use with all generations of Night Vision Devices (NVDs), but is especially suited for 3rd generation night vision technology. Aimpoint's unique band-pass coating on the front lens reflects select frequencies of red light at near 100% efficiency in order to give the highest possible dot brightness with the smallest amount of energy while transmitting nearly 100% of light in the Infrared and near-infrared part of the spectrum to provide the clearest, brightest image possible when used with a 3rd generation NVD. With 7 NVD-compatible brightness settings and 9 Daylight settings including one extra-bright setting, the CompM4 and CompM4S are ready for use around the clock. 


Technical Information: Aimpoint CompM4 and CompM4S 


•Internal voltage regulator allows the CompM4 to be used with any AA size battery
•Seven night vision compatible settings and 9 daylight settings
•QRP2 mount has twice the clamping force of the original QRP, and the mounting knob is wider and shorter to improve operation, and lessen the chance of becoming snagged on other gear
•Mount base is "keyed" into to the body of the sight to absorb recoil
•Mount base screws directly into the sight - no separate sight ring is required
•2 MOA dot for close combat and long distance engagement
•Matches perfectly with Aimpoint 3XMag, (magnifier module)
•Unequalled light transmission
•Submersible to 150 feet (45 meters)
•Vertical spacer included
•Standardized as the US Army's new M68CCO
•Improved adjustment caps are easier to remove, and are protected against impact
•Dimensions (in inches): 5.3 (l) x 3 (w) x 2.8 (h)
•Weight: 9.3 oz sight only, 11.8 oz with integrated mount
•Includes bikini style lens cover and removable ARD.
